SIMPLE: thrice
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thrice
<hw>Thrice</hw> <pr>(thr⟦imac⟧s)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>thries</ets>; <ets>thrie</ets> thrice (AS. <ets>⟦thorn⟧riga</ets>,
<ets>⟦thorn⟧riwa</ets>) + <ets>-s</ets>, the adverbal suffix. See
<er>Three</er>, and <er>-wards</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Three
times.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Thrice</xex> in vain.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Verily I say unto thee. That this night, before the cock crow,
thou shalt deny me <qex>thrice</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. xxvi.
34.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>In a threefold manner or degree; repeatedly;
very.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Thrice</qex> noble lord, let me entreat of you⟦br⟧
To pardon me.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Thrice</qex> is he armed that hath his quarrel just.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <ex>Thrice</ex> is often used, generally with an
intensive force, to form compounds which are usually of obvious meaning;
as, in <ex>thrice</ex>-blessed, <ex>thrice</ex>-favored,
<ex>thrice</ex>-hallowed, <ex>thrice</ex>-happy, <ex>thrice</ex>-told,
and the like.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thricecock</ent>⟦br⟧
